rovides multiple levels of granularity in the nutrition subnetwork. [Data: Entities (347, 346, 345, 322, 323, +more); Relationships (343, 393, 342, 324, 299, +more)]\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"summary\": \"Proteins are linked to immune defense through antibodies protecting against microorganisms\",\n      \"explanation\": \"A functional dimension is captured by the relationship stating antibodies that protect against microorganisms are proteins, directly connecting “Proteins” to “Protection against microorganisms.” This introduces a key physiological role beyond structure and nutrition, broadening the community’s depiction of proteins into health/immune function. [Data: Entities (396, 130); Relationships (382)]\\n\\nWithin the constraints of the provided data, the immune-related information is high-level (proteins as antibodies) rather than detailing pathogens, immune pathways, or clinical outcomes. Nonetheless, it establishes that proteins are not only dietary and structural components but also part of defensive biological systems. [Data: Relationships (382); Entities (396)]\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"summary\": \"Humans appear as a contextual biological reference point, including body composition information tied to proteins\",\n      \"explanation\": \"Humans are included as an entity in the community context, and “Proteins” are described as contributing substantially to human body composition, accounting for roughly 17% of the mature human body. This grounds the topic in human physiology and importance. [Data: Entities (309, 130)]\\n\\nA separate relationship ties lactose to humans via human milk composition (6%–7% lactose), which is adjacent contextual nutrition information rather than directly protein-focused. Its presence suggests the source material discusses multiple biomolecules and their roles in humans, with proteins being one major section of that broader curriculum. [Data: Relationships (278); Entities (309)]\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"rating\": 2.2,\n  \"ratin